\title: \b[Grp], the category of Groups

\sec: Definition

\jarg <grp> <category of groups> <group (iso|homo|)morphism(s|)> [\b[Grp]] is the category wherein objects are groups and morphisms are group homomorphisms.

Given groups $(G, \star)$ and $(H, *)$, a function $\phi : G \to H$ is considered a homomorphism iff $\phi(a \star b) = \phi(a) * \phi(b)$.


\sec: Properties

- Bijective homomorphisms are isomorphisms

> Morphisms preserve identities
  Assume $\phi : G \to H$ is a group morphism. Let $e$ and $\bar e$ respectively denote identities of $G$ and $H$. Then,

  \katex:
    \begin{align*}
         &  \phi(e)
      \\ &= \phi(e)\cdot \bar e
      \\ &= \phi(e)\cdot \phi(e)\cdot \phi(e)^{-1}
      \\ &= \phi(e \cdot e)\cdot \phi(e)^{-1}
      \\ &= \phi(e)\cdot \phi(e)^{-1}
      \\ &= \bar e
    \end{align*}

> Morphisms respect powers; for a morphism $\phi$ we have $\phi(a^{\pm n}) = [\phi(a)]^{\pm n}$
  For $n = 0$, observe that $\phi(a^0) = \phi(e) = e = \phi(a)^0$.

  For positive $n$, apply induction to the fact that $\phi(a^n) = \phi(a)\phi(a^{n-1})$

  For negative $n$, note that $e = \phi(e) = \phi(a^na^{-n}) = \phi(a^n)\phi(a^{-n}) = \phi(a^n)\phi(a)^{-n}$ and thus $\phi(a^n) = [\phi(a)^{-n}]^{-1} = \phi(a)^n$.

> Isomorphism preserve element order
  Proof left to the reader :O


\sec: Examples of group homomorphisms

- The function $\phi : (\mathbb Z, +) \to (\mathbb Z / n, +)$ given by $\phi(x) = \bar x$ is a homomorphism since $\overline{a + b} = \bar a + \bar b$

- Note that $e^{i\theta}e^{i\rho} = e^{i(\theta + \rho)}$. Thus letting $\text{rot}(\theta) = e^{i\theta}$ we get that $\text{rot}$ is a morphism from $(\mathbb R, +)$ into $(\mathbb C, \cdot)$. This lends itself to the nice interpretation that $\text{rot}$ takes us from translations to rotations, "wrapping" the number line around the unit circle in the complex plane; translations along $\mathbb R$ become translations around the unit circle.

- For any group $(G, \star)$ we have a homomorphism into the trivial group $(\{*\}, \cdot)$

- If $G$ is a subgroup of $H$, the inclusion function $\iota : G \to H$ is a homomorphism


\sec: Examples of group (non-)isomorphism

- $\exp : (\mathbb R, +) \to (\mathbb R^{>0}, \cdot)$ is a homomorphism since $e^{a+b} = e^ae^b$. In fact, it's an isomorphism.

- Note that $\begin{pmatrix} 1 & a \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & b \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & {a+b} \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}$. Then if we let $M(s) = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & s \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}$, we get that $M$ is an isomorphism between $(\mathbb R, +)$ and $(M(\mathbb R), \times)$ \aref [rk]
\adef: Also see "homogeneous coordinate systems" as used in computer graphics

> $\mathbb Z / 4 \ncong (\mathbb Z / 2)^2$
  Intuition. thinking of these groups as linear spaces, $\mathbb Z / 4$ has only one basis element $\bar 1$ whereas $(\mathbb Z / 2)^2$ has both $(\bar 0, \bar 1)$ and $(\bar 1, \bar 0)$ as bases

  Proof. (Note that this proof is not directly related to the intuition above.) Note that in $(\mathbb Z/2)^2$, the identity has order $0$ and every other element has order $1$. On the contrary, in $\mathbb Z/4$, the element $\bar 2$ has order $2$. Since group isomorphisms preserve order, this means that the two groups cannot be isomorphic.

