> $D_6 \cong S_3$; the dihedral group $D_6$ is isomorphic with the symmetric group $S_3$
  The group $D_6 = D_{2 \times 3}$ consists of symmetries of an equilateral triangle. By labelling the vertices of said triangle, we can associate symmetries in $D_6$ with permutations over $\{1, 2, 3\}$. For example, we can visualize reflection over the $y$-axis as

  \tikz:
    \begin{scope}[shift={(-1,0)}]
      \draw (-30:1) -- (90:1) --(210:1) -- (-30:1);
      \node at (90:1.5) {1};
      \node at (210:1.5) {2};
      \node at (-30:1.5) {3};
    \end{scope}

    \begin{scope}[shift={(7,0)}]
      \draw (-30:1) -- (90:1) --(210:1) -- (-30:1);
      \node at (90:1.5) {1};
      \node at (210:1.5) {3};
      \node at (-30:1.5) {2};
    \end{scope}

    \draw[->] (1, .2) -- (5, .2);

    \begin{scope}[shift={(3, 1)}, scale=.5]
      \draw (-30:1) -- (90:1) --(210:1) -- (-30:1);
      \draw [dashed] (-90:1) -- (90:1.5);
    \end{scope}

  and thus associate it with the permutation

  \katex:
    \begin{pmatrix}
      1 & 2 & 3 \\
      1 & 3 & 2
    \end{pmatrix}

  Note that this mapping $D_6 \to S(3)$ is an injective homomorphism.

  Further, since it's injective, and since $\lvert D_6 \rvert = 6 = \lvert S_3 \rvert$, then this mapping is in fact also surjective and is therefore an isomorphism.
